==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}} ''[[qualm#Middle English|cwalm, qualm]]'' "death, sickness, plague" from {{etyl|ang}} ''[[cwealm#Old English|cwealm]]'' (West Saxon) "death, disaster, plague," ''[[utcualm#Old English|ūtcualm]]'' (Anglian) "utter destruction," related to ''[[cwelan#Old English|cwelan]]'' "to die," ''[[cwellan#Old English|cwellan]]'' "to kill". The other suggested etymology, less satisfying, is from {{etyl|nl}} [[kwalm]] "steam, vapor, mist," which also may be ultimately from the same Germanic root as [[quell]]. Sense softened to "feeling of faintness" 1530; meaning "uneasiness, doubt" is from 1553; that of "scruple of conscience" is 1649. An indirect connection between the Old English and modern senses is plausible, via the notion of "fit of sickness."

===Pronunciation===
